      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Tyranny of the Undecided Voter,'' by Alan Wolfe (Op-Ed, Oct. 22):</p>
        <p>Mr. Wolfe is right to decry catering to the few independent, swing voters who are presumed to be the determinants in this presidential race, but he is wrong to suggest that independents ''care about the nation the least.''</p>
        <p>One need not side with Al Gore or George W. Bush to show concern for the country or civic commitment.  Mr. Wolfe's limiting of partisan identification to Republican and Democrat is a lamentable testament to the very apathy and ignorance induced by the two-party system. It is largely due to mass dissatisfaction with the two parties that many voters are undecided and fickle.</p>
        <p>Anyone looking for excitement in this presidential contest would do well to look beyond the two parties.</p>
        <p>RYAN BROOKE  Pullman, Wash., Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
